value.value: Anal fin spine that is located posteriorly adjacent to the first anal fin spine.

A small to large enameloid-covered, dentine-cored spine located on the anterior margins of one or both of the dorsal fins, found on bullhead sharks (Heterodontiformes), many dogfish sharks, fossil (but not living) batoids, chimaeroids, but lost entirely or buried in the fin bases of other shark-like fishes [Compagno, Sharks of the World].
Scale that is posteriorly adjacent to the pectoral girdle [Cloutier and Arratia 2004, character 183].
Pectoral fin lepidtrichium that is small, unbranched and unsegmented.

A paired dermal bone in Gasterosteiformes connected with the coracoid and extending posteriorly. Has also been applied to the element below the scapula and applied to the coracoid in Dipnoi. Dictionary of Ichthyology.
Caudal vertebra that is the anteriormost element of the series.
Zone of bone organ that is the ventral extension of the posttemporal.
Zone of bone organ that is part of a lepidotrich and connected to other segments by collagen fibers. These segments lend flexibility to the lepidtrich.
Lepidotrichial segment that is part of the proximal region of a caudal fin ray.

Endochondral element that separates the olfactory region from the orbit, extends medially to meet its fellow medially below the frontal bones and is bordered by the mesethmoid anteriorly. It may articulate with the autopalatine and infraorbital 1 laterally. The lateral ethmoid is paired.
Lepidotrichial segment that is part of the distal region of a caudal fin ray.
An adhesive disk modified from the pelvic fins in, for example, clingfishes (Gobiesocidae), gobies (Gobiidae) and snailfishes (Liparidae).

Distinctive first dorsal fin taking the form of a modified oval sucker-like organ with slat-like structures that open and close to create suction and take a firm hold against the skin of larger marine animals.

definition.value: For discussion of the homology of the sucking disc and dorsal fin, see Britz and Johnson (2012) (DOI: 10.1002/jmor.20063).

value.value: Soft ray that is part of the dorsal fin.
Soft ray that is part of the pelvic fin.
Region surrounding the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid.
Region of dorsal fin that is composed of spinous rays (vs soft rays).
A fossa on the posterior median part of the neural arch of a vertebra (as of a snake) that accommodates the zygosphene of the next vertebra.
Anatomical region lying to the anterior or dorsal side of the metapterygial axis.
The intercentrum unit of the axis vertebra. .
Ridge that is part of the ilium.

Tectorial restraint system is a type of ciliary restraint system for hair cells in the inner ear.  In tectorial restraint systems, the tectorial membrane restrains the cilia of the hair cells by attaching either directly to ciliary tufts or indirectly through various kinds of fibrous structure (simple fibers, fibrous strands, finger-like processes, tectorial plates) [Phylogenetic Relationships of the Lizard Families: Essays Commemorating Charles L. Camp. 1988. Eds. R Estes, GK Pregill. Stanford University Press].
Bony protuberance on the external surface of the occipital bone.[PHENOSCAPE:AD].
Elements of the sacrum joining true sacral vertebrae to pelvis [12th edition of Henderson's Dictionary of Biological terms].
Cloacal glands that secrete into the dorsal roof of the cloacal tube and or the anterior cloacal chamber. Found in male salamanders.
Cloacal gland present in males that secrete into the dorsolateral walls of the cloaca (between dorsal pelvic gland and anterior ventral pelvic gland clusters). Found in salamanders.
Foramen for the passage of the glossopharyngeal nerve IX.
The region of the upper jaw on or near the midline.

Region of the braincase which bears the facets for the hyomandibula in fishes. This region disappears in the origin of tetrapods and the space it occipied comes to contribute to the fenestra vestibulii. Clack, JA, 2001. Ch. 23, The otoccipital region. In Major Events in Early Vertebrate Evolution. Per Ahlberg editor.
Tooth of the upper jaw that is adjacent to the upper jaw symphysis.
The region of an anatomical structure (such as a tooth or jaw bone) facing the tongue.
The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, facing the lips.[PHENOSCAPE:WD].
The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, oriented posteriorly and facing the lips.
The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, facing the midline of the jaw.
Foramen for the passage of the internal carotid artery.
Foramen for the profundus or ophthalmic nerve.
Subdivision of organism that is the basal region of the pectoral fin.
Membrane organ that is usually supported by branchiostegal rays and forms the ventral and posterior wall of the gill cavity.

Cartilage element that lies between processes of the cleithrum and pelvic girdle in gobioid fishes. Posterodorsal to the ventral end of each cleithrum is a posteriorly projecting process. The pelvic intercleithral cartilage (an unpaired, median structure) forms a bridge between the processes (From Springer, 1983).

Accessory nasal sacs are found in a variety of teleosts (Webb, 1993) and likely assist in ventilating the olfactory epithelium by transmitting pressure fluctuations associated with gill irrigation from theoral cavity to the nasal (or sensory) sac (Jakubowski,1975; Webb, 1993; Belanger et al., 2003). [def from Eastman, J. T. and Lannoo, M. J. (2004)].

Sharpey's fibres (bone fibres, or perforating fibres) are a matrix of connective tissue consisting of bundles of strong collagenous fibres connecting periosteum to bone. They are part of the outer fibrous layer of periosteum, entering into the outer circumferential and interstitial lamellae of bone tissue.
A ventrally projecting spur on the posteriormost ventral procurrent caudal ray overlapping ventrally the preceding ray in various percomorphs (Johnson, 1975).
Unpaired bone that covers the base of the first pectoral ray. [Filleul and Lavoué 2001].
Region in the middle of the shaft of a long bone (e.g. humerus, femur etc).
A paired fin bud that develops into a pectoral fin.
A paired fin bud that develops into a pelvic fin.
